      q: "How does a high-pressure fogging system improve the efficiency of air-cooled condensers in commercial and industrial HVAC systems?",
      a: "Air-cooled condensers reject heat from the refrigeration cycle into the surrounding atmosphere. As outdoor ambient temperatures increase, particularly during summer afternoons or in hot climatic regions such as the Middle East, Texas, Arizona, Australia, and tropical countries, the condenser must reject heat into already hot air. This reduces the temperature difference (ΔT) between the refrigerant and the ambient air, making heat rejection less effective. When condenser efficiency decreases, the condensing pressure rises, forcing compressors to work harder to maintain the desired cooling capacity — increasing electrical demand, reducing Coefficient of Performance (COP), lowering refrigeration capacity, raising compressor discharge temperatures, and accelerating mechanical wear. Aura Air Engineering's Ultra-High-Pressure Adiabatic Fogging Systems address this by cooling the condenser intake air before it reaches the coil. Operating at 70–100 bar (1,000–1,500 PSI), the system atomizes purified water into droplets typically smaller than 10 microns, allowing nearly complete evaporation before contacting the condenser fins. Through adiabatic evaporative cooling, the surrounding air temperature can typically be reduced by 5°C to 12°C, depending on ambient dry-bulb temperature and relative humidity. The cooler intake air enables more efficient heat rejection, lowering condensing pressure and compressor workload. When integrated with Aura Air's AI-driven PLC automation, the system operates only under favourable psychrometric conditions, ensuring maximum energy savings with minimal water consumption.",
