      q: "How do high-pressure outdoor misting systems create comfortable microclimates in extreme heat without soaking people or surrounding surfaces?",
      a: "High-pressure outdoor misting systems operate on the principle of adiabatic evaporative cooling, a thermodynamic process in which water absorbs latent heat from the surrounding air as it changes from liquid to vapor. Unlike conventional low-pressure spray systems, which produce relatively large droplets that settle on surfaces, high-pressure systems atomize purified water into ultra-fine droplets — typically between 5 and 10 microns — using pumps operating at 70 to 100 bar (1,000–1,500 PSI). Because of their extremely small size, these droplets evaporate almost instantly under appropriate atmospheric conditions. The phase change removes sensible heat from the surrounding air, lowering the dry-bulb temperature before the droplets have an opportunity to wet occupants, furniture, or equipment. The effectiveness of the system depends on ambient temperature, relative humidity, airflow, nozzle placement, and droplet size distribution, all of which must be engineered to achieve rapid evaporation. Aura Air Engineering designs outdoor cooling systems using psychrometric analysis, airflow modelling, and site-specific environmental assessments rather than relying on standardized nozzle layouts. Our intelligent PLC-controlled systems continuously monitor weather conditions, automatically adjusting mist output based on real-time temperature, humidity, and wind speed to ensure maximum cooling efficiency while preventing excessive moisture accumulation. Applications include luxury resorts, outdoor dining areas, commercial plazas, stadiums, airport terminals, theme parks, industrial worker zones, rooftop restaurants, public spaces, and hospitality developments where occupant comfort directly influences customer experience, productivity, and operational success.",
